[D] Pakistan
Date: Wed 22 Sep 2021
Source: The Dawn [edited]
https://www.dawn.com/news/1647713/ncoc-lifts-additional-restrictions-in-6-districts-of-punjab-kp


As the cases of COVID-19 continue to decrease across the country, the National Command and Operation Centre (NCOC) on Tuesday [21 Sep 2021] decided to lift additional restrictions in 6 districts of Punjab and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.

However, general non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) will remain enforced across the country until [30 Sep 2021]. The situation will be reviewed on [28 Sep 2021].

The NCOC had on [4 Sep 2021] enforced restrictions in 24 districts of Punjab, KP [Khyber Pakhtunkhwa], and Islamabad. The restrictions included a ban on indoor gatherings and intercity transport and closure of educational institutions and indoor gyms. Initially, the restrictions were imposed until [12 Sep 2021] but later extended to [15 Sep 2021].

The NCOC later decided to lift the restrictions in 18 districts on [16 Sep 2021] but continued to enforce these in 6 high disease prevalence districts.

During a meeting chaired by Minister for Planning, Development and Special Initiatives Asad Umar on Tuesday [21 Sep 2021], the NCOC decided to lift additional restrictions in the remaining 6 districts -- Lahore, Faisalabad, Multan, Sargodha, and Gujrat in Punjab and Bannu in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. All educational institutions in these districts will open from [23 Sep 2021] and follow staggered opening (50% attendance, 3 days a week).

According to a document, general NPIs will remain enforced across the country until [30 Sep 2021] under which businesses of less essential services will be closed at 10 pm. However, petrol pumps, pharmacies, medical facilities, vaccination centres, clinics, milk shops, and tandoors will remain open. There will be one closed day a week and indoor and outdoor dining will be allowed till midnight. However, indoor dining and marriages will be allowed only for vaccinated people.

Public transport will be run at 50% and trains at 70% occupancy. However, cinemas will remain closed.

The policy of controlled tourism for vaccinated individuals will continue and will be ensured by the federating units. The ban on serving meals/snacks during in-flight journeys for domestic airlines will continue.

Meanwhile, the Islamabad High Court on Tuesday [22 Sep 2021] dismissed a petition suggesting that people should have the right to decide whether they want to get inoculated or not.

Chief Justice Athar Minallah observed that people across the globe had been struggling to overcome the enormous challenges for the last 2 years due to COVID-19.

"It is noted that unvaccinated persons are likely to impede the endeavors of the state to safeguard its citizens from life-threatening harm. For the reasons above, the prayers sought in the instant petition are not justiciable nor the rights of the petitioner have been infringed. The petition is, therefore, accordingly dismissed," the court ruled.

