Nepal: 788 769 / 11 072/ 372
Sri Lanka: 510 040 / 12 448 / 578
Afghanistan: 154 960 / 7198 / 180
Maldives: 84 103 / 229 / 415
Bhutan: 2599 / 3 / 4

Over the last 7 days, 212 970, 10 117, 16 774, 6780, 11 346, and 473 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and Afghanistan, respectively, compared with 217 518, 13 313, 21 623, 7402, 21 058, and 525 in the preceding 7 days, revealing almost a stable trend in India, the continuation of the sharp declining trend in Bangladesh, a decreasing trend in Pakistan, a decreasing trend in Nepal, the continuation of the sharp decreasing trend in Sri Lanka over the last 2 weeks and a stable trend in Afghanistan with a very low number of reported cases.

Live Situational Analysis on COVID-19 cases in Sri Lanka can be seen at https://hpb.health.gov.lk/covid19-dashboard/. The curve of the disease in Sri Lanka is now falling sharply. This could be the effect of the country-wide lockdown, initially imposed from the night of 20 Aug 2021 to 30 Aug 2021 which has been extended in 4 phases until 1 Oct 2021 (https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/sri-lanka-extends-covid-19-lockdown-till-october-1/article36511654.ece). The total number of laboratory-confirmed cases has crossed the milestone of 0.5 million in the country. However, the number of COVID-19 vaccine doses administered in Sri Lanka rose to 25 110 877 as of 24 Sep 2021 (https://tradingeconomics.com/sri-lanka/coronavirus-vaccination-total).

The National Command and Operation Centre (NCOC) in Pakistan enforced local restrictions including bans on indoor gatherings, intercity transport, closure of educational institutions and indoor gyms in 24 districts of Punjab, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KP), and Islamabad on 4 Sep 2021, as indicated in item [4] above, to curb the spread of the virus. The restriction imposed was initially for until 12 Sep 2021 which was extended later up to 15 Sep 2021. However, as the disease situation showed no sign of escalation, the restrictions imposed were lifted from 18 of the districts on 16 Sep 2021, and from the other 6 on 21 Sep 2021. According to the data as of 22 Sep 2021, a total of 75 955 215 vaccine doses have been administered in the country (https://covid19.who.int/region/emro/country/pk).

The daily-case positivity and number of deaths associated with COVID-19 are dropping steadily in Bangladesh. For the 1st time after a period of 6.5 months, the daily case positivity dropped below 5% (4.69%) on 21 Sep 2021. The current case positivity stands at just over 4.5%, as indicated in item [1] above. Bangladesh has a plan of vaccinating 80% of its population above the age of 18 years. So far, of the target population, only 20% have received the 1st dose and 13% have received both 1st and 2nd doses (http://103.247.238.92/webportal/pages/covid19-vaccination-update.php).

After a steady falling of new cases over the preceding 2 weeks almost a stable trend of new cases was noticed in India last week [week of 13 Sep 2021]. As indicated in item [2] above, Kerala state contributed 50% of the new cases reported. Out of the 36 States and Union Territories in the country 19 including Kerala are now showing a decreasing trend of new cases, according to the counts as of 24 Sep 2021 at 8:00 AM IST compared to the counts in the previous 24 hours. As of 24 Sep 2021 at 8.00 AM IST, 841 518 026 doses of the COVID-19 vaccines have been administered in India (https://www.mohfw.gov.in/). India set a single-day record of administering more than 25 million doses of COVID-19 vaccine by midnight 17 Sep 2021 (https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/india-administers-record-2-crore-50-lakh-covid-19-vaccine-doses-in-a-single-day-on-september-17-2021/article36512270.ece).

